<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,989,2021]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,451,1059,1082]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">
<typeStatus box="[199,303,1059,1082]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Holotype</typeStatus>
description.
</emphasis>
Length 
<quantity box="[554,659,1059,1082]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.03" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" unit="mm" value="10.3">10.3 mm</quantity>
. Colour black dorsally, with yellow spots on pronotum, elytra and lateroterga. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[277,337,1094,1117]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Head</emphasis>
with frons dark green, glabrous. Clypeus with thin transverse carina at the base. Antennae serrate from 4th antennomere. Eyes large, therefore with reduced cheeks. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[787,901,1131,1154]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Pronotum</emphasis>
depressed at the sides: the depressions covered by yellow pubescence. Posterior angles acute. Premarginal carina entire. Marginal carinae joined before the base. Prosternal lobe with anterior margin slightly sinuate. Prosternal process straight, parallel sided. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1084,1197,1201,1224]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Scutellum</emphasis>
transversely carinate. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,224,1235,1258]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Elytra</emphasis>
with apex ending in a long and robust spine. Disc with 
<docIssue box="[811,824,1235,1258]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">3</docIssue>
pairs of yellow pubescent spots, respectively on the base, at basal ⅓ and at apical ⅔. Lateroterga with spots of similar pubescence. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[956,1073,1270,1293]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Underside</emphasis>
with gold reflections. Two small tubercles in the median part of the basal ventrite, as in the male of the Palearctic species 
<taxonomicName authority="(Illiger, 1803)" authorityName="Illiger" authorityYear="1803" baseAuthorityName="Illiger" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[1124,1432,1304,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustulus">
<emphasis box="[1124,1270,1304,1328]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">A. angustulus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Illiger" box="[1286,1424,1305,1328]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" refString="Illiger, J. C. W. (1803) Verzeichniss der in Portugall einheimischen Kafer. Erste Lieferung. Magazin fur Insectenkunde, 2, 186 - 258." type="journal article" year="1803">Illiger, 1803</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Small and scarcely visible spots of pubescence at the base of the ventrites. Metepisternum covered with yellow pubescence. Apex of the last visible ventrite rounded. Apex of the last visible tergite whith an elongated and pointed process. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[244,298,1409,1432]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Legs</emphasis>
metallic gold. All claws bifid, but with the internal tooth shorter. Metatarsus longer than metatibia. Tarsal formulae: 1&gt;2+3+4; 2&gt;3+4. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[460,569,1443,1466]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Aedeagus</emphasis>
strongly sclerotized, parallel, slender, thin, with apex of median lobe acute (fig. 1c).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="423" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,989,2021]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,327,1513,1536]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species in named after the ambassador Luigi Scotto for the support provided during the author’s researches in Africa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="423" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,989,2021]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,1582,1605]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Remarks.</emphasis>
The label of 
<taxonomicName authority="Curletti &amp; Dutto, 2017" authorityName="Curletti &amp; Dutto" authorityYear="2017" box="[453,610,1581,1605]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scottoi" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[453,610,1581,1605]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Agrilus scottoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[617,675,1582,1605]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
has little data and the species is very similar to some taxa occurring in the 
<collectingRegion box="[191,278,1617,1640]" country="Democratic Republic of the Congo" name="Orientale" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Oriental</collectingRegion>
Region, and for this reason, for several years, we did not describe it, however, after further study, we have decided to describe it.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="424" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,989,2021]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">
<taxonomicName authority="Curletti &amp; Dutto, 2017" authorityName="Curletti &amp; Dutto" authorityYear="2017" box="[199,358,1685,1709]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scottoi" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[199,358,1685,1709]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Agrilus scottoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[368,428,1686,1709]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
has a mixture of characters seen in the subgenera 
<taxonomicName authority="Curletti, 1998" authorityName="Curletti" authorityYear="1998" box="[995,1254,1686,1709]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Nigritius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[995,1090,1686,1709]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Nigritius</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Curletti" box="[1100,1254,1686,1709]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" refString="Curletti, G. (1998) Notes on metatarsal morphology in the genus Agrilus and a proposed redefinition of its subgenera in the Afrotropical region (Coleoptera Buprestidae). Bollettino della Societa Entomologica Italiana, 130 (2), 124 - 134." type="journal article" year="1998">Curletti, 1998</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Curletti, 1998" authorityName="Curletti" authorityYear="1998" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Pantherina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1316,1436,1685,1709]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Pantherina</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Curletti" box="[151,304,1721,1744]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" refString="Curletti, G. (1998) Notes on metatarsal morphology in the genus Agrilus and a proposed redefinition of its subgenera in the Afrotropical region (Coleoptera Buprestidae). Bollettino della Societa Entomologica Italiana, 130 (2), 124 - 134." type="journal article" year="1998">Curletti, 1998</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. The elytral apices, ending with a strong spine, and the conformation of the metatarsus are typical of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Curletti" authorityYear="1998" box="[260,380,1754,1778]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Pantherina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[260,380,1754,1778]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Pantherina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the presence of an elongated pointed process at the apex of last visible tergite, places this species without a doubt in the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authority="Curletti, 1998" authorityName="Curletti" authorityYear="1998" box="[581,833,1790,1813]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Nigritius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[581,676,1790,1813]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Nigritius</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Curletti" box="[682,833,1790,1813]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" refString="Curletti, G. (1998) Notes on metatarsal morphology in the genus Agrilus and a proposed redefinition of its subgenera in the Afrotropical region (Coleoptera Buprestidae). Bollettino della Societa Entomologica Italiana, 130 (2), 124 - 134." type="journal article" year="1998">Curletti, 1998</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,989,2021]" lastBlockId="1.[151,1436,151,209]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="424" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">
Within the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Curletti" authorityYear="1998" box="[425,520,1825,1848]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Nigritius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[425,520,1825,1848]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Nigritius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, several species have ochraceous pubescent spots on the elytra, but the majority have 4 pairs of spots and the elytral apices lack strong spines: among these, the most similar in body form are 
<taxonomicName authority="Obenberger, 1931" authorityName="Obenberger" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jedlickai">
<emphasis box="[1312,1436,1858,1882]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">A. jedlickai</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Obenberger" box="[151,343,1894,1917]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" refString="Obenberger, J. (1931) Agrilenstudien I. (Col. Bupr.). Entomologisches Nachrichtenblatt, 5, 54 - 71." type="journal article" year="1931">Obenberger, 1931</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Obenberger 1931" authorityName="Obenberger" authorityYear="1931" box="[397,721,1894,1917]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="patricius">
<emphasis box="[397,522,1894,1917]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">A. patricius</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Obenberger" box="[531,721,1894,1917]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" refString="Obenberger, J. (1931) Agrilenstudien I. (Col. Bupr.). Entomologisches Nachrichtenblatt, 5, 54 - 71." type="journal article" year="1931">Obenberger 1931</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Only one species has both apical elytral spines and three pairs of elytral spots: 
<taxonomicName authority="Burgeon, 1941" authorityName="Burgeon" authorityYear="1941" box="[293,580,1928,1952]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="overlaeti">
<emphasis box="[293,417,1928,1952]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">A. overlaeti</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Burgeon" box="[423,580,1929,1952]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" refString="Burgeon, L. (1941) Catalogues raisonnes de la faune entomologique du Congo Belge. Coleopteres. Buprestides. Annales du Musee du Congo Belge, C. (Zool.), Series III (II), Tome V, Fasc. 3, 121 - 276." type="book chapter" year="1941">Burgeon, 1941</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from the 
<collectingRegion box="[683,757,1929,1952]" country="Democratic Republic of the Congo" name="Bas-Congo" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">
<collectingCountry box="[683,757,1929,1952]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Congo</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
, but this differs in having large spots on the ventrites and a large yellow pubescent spot on the frons. Among the species of subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Curletti" authorityYear="1998" box="[874,994,1962,1986]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Pantherina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[874,994,1962,1986]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">Pantherina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the most similar one is A. 
<emphasis box="[1285,1436,1963,1986]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="423">portonovencis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kerremans" box="[151,339,1998,2021]" pageId="0" pageNumber="423" refString="Kerremans, C. (1903) Coleoptera Serricornia, Fam. Buprestidae. In: Wytsman, P. (Ed.), Genera Insectorum. Fasc. 12 b, 12 c &amp; 12 d. Verteneuil &amp; Desmet, Bruxelles, pp. 49 - 338." type="book chapter" year="1903">Kerremans, 1903</bibRefCitation>
, widely distributed in Western Africa, differing only in the absence of the apical spines and ventrites with pubescent spots. Another species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Obenberger, 1935" authorityName="Obenberger" authorityYear="1935" box="[588,891,151,175]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="woodi">
<emphasis box="[588,687,151,175]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="424">A. woodi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Obenberger" box="[697,891,152,175]" pageId="1" pageNumber="424" refString="Obenberger, J. (1935) De regionis aethiopicae speciebus generis Agrili novis (Col. Bupr.). Nove druhy krascc z rodu Agrilus z aethiopske oblasti. Acta Entomologica Musaei Nationalis Pragae, 13, 149 - 210." type="journal article" year="1935">Obenberger, 1935</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[964,1045,152,175]" name="Malawi" pageId="1" pageNumber="424">Malawi</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1104,1203,152,175]" name="Tanzania" pageId="1" pageNumber="424">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
, although having the apical spines, has 6 pairs of white pubescent elytral spots.
</paragraph>
